3001.0 Context and role of this study in the overall development path: Provide any detailed Go/No Go criteria, in line with the iDP, for internal decision making. These criteria are important to ensure the study design will allow for sound and informative decision making. Ask the Project Biostatistician for slides that are available to help prepare these criteria. REMOVE this section in any external disclosure, including the protocol. To evaluate whether M7824 improves efficacy as a first-line (1L) therapy in combination with gemcitabine plus cisplatin for participants with locally advanced or metastatic biliary tract cancer (BTC), a clinical proof-of-concept, randomized, controlled Phase II/III study in participants with BTC will be initiated. This is the first study of immuno-oncology therapy in 1L BTC to investigate the outcomes, dual primary endpoints, progression-free survival (PFS) time endpoints, and overall survival (OS). The key secondary endpoint is objective response. This study has an adaptive design that, without changing the inclusion and exclusion criteria for enrollment or randomization scheme, allows the expansion of the Phase II study into a Phase III study by adding additional participants. The planned total sample size is 150 or 500 in addition to the safety run-in (i.e., 150 participants for the Phase II part and an additional 350 participants for the Phase III part). If the odds ratio in confirmed objective response is ≥ 1.6 or the hazard ratio (HR) in PFS is < 0.75 at the interim analysis (IA) for adaptation decision with 150 participants, an additional 350 participants will be randomized. Assuming a true objective response difference of 15% and a true PFS hazard ratio (HR) of 0.65, this threshold is met with a probability of 93%, whereas if the true objective response difference is 0% and the PFS HR is 1.0 or worse, respectively, this threshold would be met with a probability of 19% or less. The planned first participant first dose is in Q3 2019. The planned analyses are shown in the table and figure below. Cohort Sequence of Analyses Open-label Safety Run in Safety assessment in 3 6 Asian sites’ cohort and 6 Non-Asian sites’ cohort or up to 12 participants in each cohort; DLT will be evaluated in the first 21 days. Randomized, IA for adaptation decision Analysis of PFS and objective response, including both confirmed and unconfirmed response when the target number of 80 PFS events have occurred in a total of 150 participants expected at 12 months from randomization. The ITT analysis set will be used for the analysis. Randomized, Phase II part PFS PA and OS PA when the target number of 109 PFS events have occurred in a total of 150 participants expected at 18 months from randomization. The ITT analysis set will be used for the analysis. Randomized, Phase III part PFS IA when the target number of 184 PFS events have occurred, expected at 23 months from start of randomization. PFS PA and OS IA when the target number of 301 PFS events have occurred, expected at 29 months from start of randomization. OS PA when 353 OS events have occurred, expected at 43 months from start of randomization. The ITT analysis set will be used for these analyses. 24003.0 PFS according to RECIST 1.1 assessed by IRC PFS is defined as the time from randomization to the date of the first documentation of objective PD as assessed by the IRC according to RECIST 1.1 or death due to any cause in the absence of documented PD, whichever occurs first. Progression or death, which occurred later than 2 scheduled tumor assessment intervals after the last evaluable response assessment will be censored at the date of the last evaluable response assessment for PFS analyses. Kaplan-Meier estimates and associated statistics (PFS rates at 3, 6, 9, 12, and 24 months; median PFS) and corresponding 95% CIs will be presented by treatment group. Test statistics of stratified log-rank test (same strata as used for randomization) will be presented. 33001.0 Symbol Definition
33002.0 Ae The cumulative amount excreted during a complete dose interval at steady state. Amount_Recovered = Σ(Concentration * Volume) from T1 to T2, where T1 and T2 denote the start and end time of the dose interval at steady state respectively.
33003.0 Ae% The cumulative percentage of dose excreted during a complete dose interval at steady state. Percent_Recovered = 100*Amount_Recovered/Dose.
33004.0 Ae0-t The cumulative amount excreted from time zero (= dosing time) to the end of the current collection interval after dosing. Amount_Recovered = Σ(Concentration * Volume)
33005.0 Ae0-t% The cumulative percentage of dose excreted from time zero (= dosing time) to the end of the current collection interval after dosing. Percent_Recovered = 100*Amount_Recovered/Dose
33006.0 Ae0- The cumulative amount excreted from time zero (dosing time) to infinity. Ae0-∞=Ae0-t+((Ae0-(t-1)-Ae0-t)/(tlast-1-tlast))/λz where z is the excretion rate or Ae0-∞ = (Ae0-t / AUC0-t ) * AUC0-
33007.0 Ae0- The cumulative percentage of the dose that is excreted from time zero (= dosing time) to infinity. Percent_Recovered = 100*Amount_Recovered/Dose
33008.0 AUC The area under the concentration-time curve (AUC) over the dosing interval from T1=0 h to T2=τ h. Calculated using the mixed log-linear trapezoidal rule (linear up, log down). For single dose, AUCτ is calculated as a partial area with the defined time range. In multiple dose profiles AUC is calculated at steady state from one pre-dose time point to the dosing interval time. In cases where the actual observation time is not equal to the scheduled observation time AUC will be calculated based on the estimated concentration at τ hours, and not the concentration at the actual observation time.
33009.0 AUCτ /Dose The Dose normalized AUC over the interval from T1=0 h to T2=τ h. Normalized using actual dose, using the formula AUCτ /Dose.
33010.0 AUC0-t The area under the concentration-time curve (AUC) from time zero (= dosing time) to the last sampling time (tlast) at which the concentration is at or above the lower limit of quantification. Calculated using the mixed log-linear trapezoidal rule (linear up, log down).
33011.0 AUC0-t,adj The area under the concentration-time curve (AUC) from time zero (= dosing time) to the last sampling time, adjusted to the concentration at baseline. Calculated either directly from baseline corrected concentration data and the mixed log-linear trapezoidal rule (linear up, log down), or using the formula: AUC0-t,adj = AUC0-t – (baseline * t).
33012.0 AUC0-t /Dose The Dose normalized AUC from time zero to the last sampling time (tlast) at which the concentration is at or above the lower limit of quantification. Normalized using the actual dose, using the formula AUC0-t /Dose.
33013.0 AUC0- The AUC from time zero (dosing time) extrapolated to infinity, based on the predicted value for the concentration at tlast , as estimated using the linear regression from λz determination. AUC0-∞=AUC0-t+Clast pred/ λz
33014.0 AUC0-(Obs) The AUC from time zero (dosing time) extrapolated to infinity, based on the observed value for the concentration at tlast , AUC0-∞=AUC0-t+Clast obs/ λz Predicted/observed AUC0-∞ should be selected as appropriate.
33015.0 AUC0- adj Baseline corrected AUC0-∞., calculated directly from baseline corrected concentration data. Note that when baseline correction is required (e.g. endogenous compound) AUC0-∞ and all related parameters (e.g. clearance, volume of distribution, λz) should be calculated from baseline corrected concentration data only. Either the observed or predicted AUC0-∞ should be used, depending on the study specific requirements.
33016.0 AUC0-∞ /Dose The Dose normalized AUC from time zero extrapolated to infinity. Normalized using actual dose, using the formula AUC0-∞ /Dose. Either the observed or predicted AUC0-∞ should be used, depending on the study specific requirements.
33017.0 AUCextra% The AUC from time tlast extrapolated to infinity given as percentage of AUC0- . AUCextra = (extrapolated area/AUC0-∞)*100. Either the observed or predicted AUC0-∞ should be used, depending on the study specific requirements.
33018.0 C0 The initial (or fictive) concentration at time zero for bolus IV models. C0 is equal to the first observed concentration value if that value occurs at the dose time. Otherwise, it is estimated by back-extrapolating from the first two concentration values.
33019.0 Cav The average concentration at steady state. Cav = AUC /.
33020.0 CL The total body clearance of study intervention following intravenous administration. CL = Dose i.v /AUC0-∞. Either the observed or predicted AUC0-∞ should be used, depending on the study specific requirements.
33021.0 CLNonR The non-renal clearance of study intervention. CLNonR = CL- CLR.
33022.0 CL/f The apparent total body clearance of study intervention following extravascular administration, taking into account the fraction of dose absorbed. CL/f = Dose p.o. /AUC0-∞. Either the observed or predicted AUC0-∞ should be used, depending on the study specific requirements.
33023.0 Clast The observed concentration at the last sampling time (tlast) at which the concentration is at or above the lower limit of quantification
33024.0 Clast pred The predicted concentration at the last sampling time (tlast), calculated from the log-linear regression line for λz determination.
33025.0 CLR The renal clearance of study intervention. CLR = Ae0-∞/AUC0-∞ or Ae0-t/AUC0-t
33026.0 CLSS The apparent total body clearance of study intervention at steady state following intravenous administration. CLss = Dose i.v./ AUC.
33027.0 CLSS/f The apparent total body clearance of study intervention at steady state following extravascular administration, taking into account the fraction of dose absorbed. CLss/f = Dose p.o. / AUC.
33028.0 CLRSS The renal clearance of study intervention at steady state. CLRSS = Ae / AUC.
33029.0 Cmax Maximum observed concentration
33030.0 Cmax,adj Baseline adjusted Cmax. Cmax,adj = Cmax-baseline
33031.0 Cmax/Dose The Dose normalized maximum concentration. Normalized using the actual dose, and the formula Cmax /Dose.
33032.0 Cmin The minimum observed concentration during a complete dosing interval
33033.0 Ctrough The concentration observed immediately before next dosing (corresponding to pre-dose or trough concentration for multiple dosing)
33034.0 f Bioavailability of test in relation to reference; f =
33035.0 F Bioavailability (%); F = * 100
33036.0 MRT0-t Mean residence time of study intervention in the body from time zero (dosing time) to the last sampling time (tlast) at which the concentration is at or above the lower limit of quantification. MRTlast = (AUMC0-t/AUC0-t) - T/2, where T represents infusion duration. For non-infusion, T=0.
33037.0 MRT0- Mean residence time of study intervention in the body from time zero (dosing time) extrapolated to infinity. MRT0- = (AUMC0-/AUC0-)-T/2, where T represents infusion duration. For non-infusion T= 0. Either the observed or predicted AUMC0-∞ should be used, depending on the study specific requirements.
33038.0 MRTSS The mean residence time at steady state. For non-infusion: MRTss = (AUMC + AUC0- AUC))/ AUC For infusion : MRTss = ((AUMC + AUC0- AUC))/ AUC ) - T/2, where T represents infusion duration. Either the observed or predicted AUMC0-∞ should be used, depending on the study specific requirements.
33039.0 PTF The peak trough fluctuation within a complete dosing interval at steady state. PTF = 100*(Cmax-Cmin)/Cav.
33040.0 Racc(AUC) The accumulation factor to assess the increase in exposure until steady state is reached. Racc(AUC)= (AUC after multiple dose (at steady state)) / (AUC after single dose)
33041.0 Racc(AUC0-t) The accumulation factor to assess the increase in exposure via AUC0-t. Racc(AUC0-t)= (AUC0-t after multiple dose (at steady state)) / (AUC0-t after single dose). Evaluate consistency of tlast if this measure is to be used.
33042.0 Racc(AUC0-∞) The accumulation factor to assess the increase in exposure via AUC0-∞. Racc(AUC0-∞)= (AUC0-∞ after multiple dose (at steady state)) / (AUC0-∞ after single dose)
33043.0 Racc(Cmax) The accumulation factor to assess the increase in maximum concentration until steady state is reached. Racc(Cmax) = (Cmax after multiple dose (at steady state) )/ (Cmax after single dose)
33044.0 Swing The degree of fluctuation over one dosing interval at steady state. Swing = 100*(Cmax-Cmin)/Cmin
33045.0 T Actual duration of a constant rate infusion. Calculated from CRF data: T= Infusion end time – Infusion start time
33046.0 t1/2 Apparent terminal half-life. t1/2 = ln (2)/λz
33047.0 tlag The time prior to the first measurable (non-zero) concentration (for extravascular input only)
33048.0 tlast The last sampling time at which the concentration is at or above the lower limit of quantification
33049.0 tmax The time to reach the maximum observed concentration collected during a dosing interval (unless otherwise defined, take the 1st occurrence in case of multiple/identical Cmax values)
33050.0 tmid Midpoint of collection interval Calculated from the concentration-time profile: (ti-1+ti)/2
33051.0 tmin The time to reach the minimum observed concentration collected during a dosing interval
33052.0 Volume Urine Volume sampled during a defined collection period
33053.0 VSS An estimate of the apparent volume of distribution at steady state following intravenous administration. Vss = MRT0- *CL following single dose. Vss = MRTss *CLss following multiple dose
33054.0 VZ The apparent volume of distribution during the terminal phase following intravenous administration. VZ = Dose/(AUC0-∞*λz) following single dose. VZ = Dose/( AUC*λz) following multiple dose.
33055.0 VZ/f The apparent volume of distribution during the terminal phase following extravascular administration, based on the fraction of dose absorbed. Vz/f = Dose/(AUC0-∞*λz) following single dose. Vz/f = Dose/( AUC*λz) following multiple dose.
33056.0 z Terminal first order (elimination) rate constant. Determined from the terminal slope of the log-transformed concentration curve using linear regression on terminal data points of the curve
